    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-20T22:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-20T22:36:00-05:00" n="707"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d707">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/11547, 11564.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Canada</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Vera Cruz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-20T21:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 20, 1914, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Steamer <hi rend="italic">Ypiranga</hi>, owned by Hamburg-American Line, will
                    arrive tomorrow from Germany with 200 machine guns and 15,000,000 cartridges;
                    will go to Pier 4 and start discharging at 10.30. There will be 30 cars on the
                    pier to load the munitions of war direct from the steamer; trains of 10 cars
                    each will be sent out over the Mexican Railway as soon as loaded, making three
                    trains in all.</p>
                <p>There are now here 1,200 standard and narrow-gauge freight-cars including [list
                    of cars]; 10 narrow-gauge engines and 10 standard-gauge engines. Plenty of coal
                    and oil in railroad yards.</p>
                <p>The general in command states that he will not fight but will leave with all
                    soldiers and rolling-stock tomorrow, tearing up the track behind him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Canada</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
